WEBVTT

1
00:03:02.577 --> 00:03:03.869
Bye, guys.

2
00:03:03.911 --> 00:03:05.329
It's three years.

3
00:03:05.371 --> 00:03:06.581
Three years together.

4
00:03:06.622 --> 00:03:07.915
The lads.

5
00:03:07.956 --> 00:03:09.708
Me and you?

6
00:03:09.750 --> 00:03:12.002
We'll see each
other again. Really?

7
00:03:12.044 --> 00:03:12.545
They're not going, are they?

8
00:03:13.921 --> 00:03:16.591
Group hug!

9
00:03:16.632 --> 00:03:18.842
See you, ladies! See you later.

10
00:03:21.345 --> 00:03:23.097
Group hug.

11
00:03:23.138 --> 00:03:24.723
Oh, whoa, whoa, whoa!

12
00:03:25.849 --> 00:03:27.351
Tilly?

13
00:03:27.393 --> 00:03:28.769
Callum!

14
00:03:28.810 --> 00:03:30.438
Tilly, come on.
It's time to go home.

15
00:03:30.479 --> 00:03:32.147
Come on. Callum!

16
00:03:33.232 --> 00:03:34.483
Ow!

17
00:03:41.031 --> 00:03:43.117
You know,
we've never actually met.

18
00:03:43.158 --> 00:03:43.992
Actually, we have.
Several times.

19
00:03:44.034 --> 00:03:46.036
Have we?

20
00:03:46.078 --> 00:03:48.414
You gatecrashed my
birthday party, called me Julie,

21
00:03:48.456 --> 00:03:49.540
and spilled red wine
down my top.

22
00:03:49.582 --> 00:03:50.374
Ouch.

23
00:03:51.584 --> 00:03:52.793
Well, I'm sorry about that.

24
00:03:52.834 --> 00:03:54.002
No, not at all.

25
00:03:54.044 --> 00:03:54.920
You were delightful.

26
00:03:54.962 --> 00:03:56.130
Was I?

27
00:03:56.171 --> 00:03:58.006
No. No, you weren't.

28
00:03:58.048 --> 00:04:00.175
Look, if you're
not Julie, then...

29
00:04:00.217 --> 00:04:01.636
I'm Emma. Emma.

30
00:04:01.677 --> 00:04:03.178
Emma Morley. Emma Morley.

31
00:04:04.179 --> 00:04:05.681
Listen, I'll walk you home.

32
00:04:09.184 --> 00:04:10.478
So this is me.

33
00:04:10.519 --> 00:04:12.146
Shh! Welcome home.

34
00:04:12.187 --> 00:04:14.189
So debate is fine,
but anyone can talk...

35
00:04:19.194 --> 00:04:21.863
Just sometimes,
action's what's needed.

36
00:04:21.905 --> 00:04:24.408
To change the world.
I completely agree.

37
00:04:26.243 --> 00:04:29.204
So what are you gonna be
when you're, I don't know, 40?

38
00:04:29.246 --> 00:04:30.706
Forty?

39
00:04:30.789 --> 00:04:33.709
Can I say famous? Horribly rich?

40
00:04:33.750 --> 00:04:35.836
Terrible.
You're so terribly posh.

41
00:04:37.004 --> 00:04:38.297
Where are you going?

42
00:04:38.339 --> 00:04:39.256
I'm just gonna
go brush my teeth.

43
00:04:39.298 --> 00:04:40.508
You know, booze and fags and...

44
00:04:40.549 --> 00:04:41.467
I don't mind.

45
00:04:41.509 --> 00:04:43.511
I do.

46
00:04:43.552 --> 00:04:45.095
Listen, won't be a minute.

47
00:04:47.014 --> 00:04:48.474
No playing with yourself
while I'm gone.

48
00:04:50.934 --> 00:04:51.893
What?

49
00:05:04.490 --> 00:05:07.242
All right, concentrate.

50
00:05:07.284 --> 00:05:10.245
Concentrate.
Do not cock this up!

51
00:05:24.885 --> 00:05:26.762
Oh, you're going?

52
00:05:26.803 --> 00:05:29.431
Well, it's getting light out,
so I thought I could just...

53
00:05:29.473 --> 00:05:31.517
You should go if you want to go.

54
00:05:31.559 --> 00:05:32.851
It's very poignant.
Very bittersweet.

55
00:05:32.893 --> 00:05:34.520
Really I just thought you
might wanna get some sleep.

56
00:05:34.562 --> 00:05:35.854
I don't have to go.

57
00:05:35.896 --> 00:05:36.855
No, no, go. I'm not bothered.

58
00:05:36.897 --> 00:05:38.440
Sneak off.

59
00:05:38.482 --> 00:05:40.025
I wasn't sneaking off.

60
00:05:40.067 --> 00:05:41.109
Jump out the window
for all I care.

61
00:05:41.151 --> 00:05:42.861
It's five floors up, mind.

62
00:05:42.903 --> 00:05:44.279
Look, I'll stay. All right?

63
00:05:45.280 --> 00:05:47.241
I'll stay.

64
00:05:47.282 --> 00:05:48.492
Come on.

65
00:05:52.496 --> 00:05:54.331
Sorry, I'm no good at this.

66
00:05:56.124 --> 00:05:58.335
It's just whenever
I go to bed with someone,

67
00:05:58.377 --> 00:06:01.880
I always end up
either laughing or weeping,

68
00:06:01.922 --> 00:06:03.340
and it could be nice to go
for something in between.

69
00:06:03.382 --> 00:06:06.260
Look, that's fine.

70
00:06:06.301 --> 00:06:08.721
That's fine. Maybe we
could just be friends.

71
00:06:09.930 --> 00:06:12.516
Okay. Friends.

72
00:06:24.319 --> 00:06:27.489
Of course, you know it's Saint
Swithin's Day today, don't you?

73
00:06:27.531 --> 00:06:29.991
What is?

74
00:06:30.033 --> 00:06:33.495
Well, today. Saint Swithin's
Day, the 15th of July.

75
00:06:33.537 --> 00:06:35.539
How do you know that?

76
00:06:35.581 --> 00:06:38.333
Well, he was buried in
Winchester Cathedral,

77
00:06:38.375 --> 00:06:40.294
which is where I went to school.

78
00:06:40.335 --> 00:06:41.837
Well, la-dee-da.

79
00:06:41.878 --> 00:06:43.004
La-dee-da.

80
00:06:44.881 --> 00:06:47.926
You know, there's a poem.

81
00:06:47.968 --> 00:06:51.806
"If on Saint Swithin's Day,
it doth rain

82
00:06:51.847 --> 00:06:55.976
"something, something,
something remain."

83
00:06:56.017 --> 00:06:57.728
Dexter, that's beautiful.

84
00:06:57.770 --> 00:06:59.647
Shut up.

85
00:06:59.688 --> 00:07:01.774
Let's get some sleep.

86
00:07:09.239 --> 00:07:10.741
But, Dex.

87
00:07:10.783 --> 00:07:12.242
Em?

88
00:07:12.284 --> 00:07:13.952
If it doesn't rain...

89
00:07:13.994 --> 00:07:15.203
Mmm-hmm?

90
00:07:17.998 --> 00:07:20.083
do you want to do
something? Me and you?

91
00:07:21.418 --> 00:07:22.377
Mmm-hmm.

92
00:07:26.465 --> 00:07:27.382
- Are you all right?
- Lift, lift.

93
00:07:27.424 --> 00:07:29.050
Okay, well, I'm coming up.

94
00:07:32.387 --> 00:07:34.014
Couldn't you have just hired
someone to move this stuff?

95
00:07:34.055 --> 00:07:34.973
No.

96
00:07:36.266 --> 00:07:37.768
Look, I would have paid.

97
00:07:37.810 --> 00:07:40.187
All right, lift from your end.

98
00:07:40.228 --> 00:07:41.856
You've obviously never
done a day's work in your life.

99
00:07:41.897 --> 00:07:45.818
Look, seriously, Em,
my plane leaves in four hours.

100
00:07:45.860 --> 00:07:47.653
All right, well, all the more
reason why you should lift.

101
00:07:47.695 --> 00:07:48.904
God's sake.

102
00:07:50.614 --> 00:07:51.866
Look, I'm doing you a favor.

103
00:07:51.907 --> 00:07:53.575
And I am so, so grateful.

104
00:07:53.617 --> 00:07:54.993
Stop whinging.

105
00:07:57.621 --> 00:07:59.623
I bet this bed
could tell some stories.

106
00:07:59.665 --> 00:08:02.710
Yeah, short stories.
Horror stories.

107
00:08:02.751 --> 00:08:05.379
Welcome to London.
Well, lift it.

108
00:08:10.050 --> 00:08:11.927
I think I'm gonna
be very happy here.

109
00:08:11.968 --> 00:08:13.303
What is that smell?

110
00:08:13.345 --> 00:08:14.930
Onions.

111
00:08:14.971 --> 00:08:16.097
Onions and disappointment.

112
00:08:16.765 --> 00:08:18.183
Right.

113
00:08:18.225 --> 00:08:19.810
No, it's not that bad.

114
00:08:19.852 --> 00:08:22.187
It's nothing
that a lick of paint

115
00:08:22.229 --> 00:08:24.606
and a nuclear warhead can't fix.

116
00:08:24.648 --> 00:08:27.943
I've got my typewriter. I've
got my books. I'm in London.

117
00:08:27.984 --> 00:08:29.444
I think it's
going to be all right.

118
00:08:29.486 --> 00:08:30.696
I might actually
get things done.

119
00:08:30.738 --> 00:08:32.406
You know, you might
actually meet someone.

120
00:08:32.447 --> 00:08:33.407
Dexter, please.

121
00:08:33.448 --> 00:08:34.658
A nice guy.

122
00:08:34.700 --> 00:08:36.660
Sensitive, wears a cardigan.

123
00:08:36.702 --> 00:08:38.119
I told you I'm not interested
in any of that.

124
00:08:38.161 --> 00:08:40.205
Matching glasses,
matching opinions.

125
00:08:40.247 --> 00:08:41.874
I'm actually glad
you're going to India.

126
00:08:41.916 --> 00:08:44.835
Good, 'cause I'm leaving.
I've got to catch my flight.

127
00:08:44.877 --> 00:08:46.628
Already?

128
00:08:46.670 --> 00:08:47.922
Yeah, I'm sorry.

129
00:08:50.591 --> 00:08:53.343
Well, go on then. Find yourself.

130
00:08:53.385 --> 00:08:55.637
Keep sending me those letters.

131
00:08:55.679 --> 00:08:57.848
Long ones. I will.

132
00:08:57.890 --> 00:08:59.057
And have fun, Em.

133
00:08:59.099 --> 00:09:00.517
Of course.

134
00:09:00.559 --> 00:09:03.144
You know, it is allowed.

135
00:09:03.186 --> 00:09:04.897
You know, I've got a feeling
that this time next year

136
00:09:04.939 --> 00:09:05.981
you're going to
take London by storm.

137
00:09:14.406 --> 00:09:15.741
What is
the difference between...

138
00:09:15.783 --> 00:09:17.242
A tortilla is
either corn or wheat.

139
00:09:17.284 --> 00:09:19.327
But a corn tortilla
folded and filled is a taco,

140
00:09:19.369 --> 00:09:21.288
whereas a filled
wheat tortilla is a burrito.

141
00:09:21.329 --> 00:09:23.331
Deep fry a burrito,
it's a chimichanga.

142
00:09:23.373 --> 00:09:26.084
Toast a tortilla, it's a tostada.
Roll it, it's an enchilada.

143
00:09:28.796 --> 00:09:30.130
Is there any chance
you could repeat that?

144
00:09:33.174 --> 00:09:35.469
Hello. I'm Ian. Ian Whitehead.

145
00:09:35.510 --> 00:09:37.721
The new boy.

146
00:09:37.763 --> 00:09:38.973
Welcome to
the graveyard of ambition.

147
00:09:41.516 --> 00:09:43.518
The kitchen. All right, mate.

148
00:09:43.560 --> 00:09:45.312
What these guys
can't do with a microwave

149
00:09:45.353 --> 00:09:46.480
and a deep-fat fryer.

150
00:09:46.521 --> 00:09:48.523
Hey, you!

151
00:09:48.565 --> 00:09:50.776
Your basic Tex-Mex food groups.

152
00:09:50.818 --> 00:09:52.611
Cheese on top of
chicken under guacamole

153
00:09:52.653 --> 00:09:55.363
on top of beans
under rice on top of beef.

154
00:09:55.405 --> 00:09:58.826
Word of warning,
avoid the jumbo prawns.

155
00:09:58.867 --> 00:10:01.411
It's like Russian Roulette.
One in six will kill you.

156
00:10:01.453 --> 00:10:02.203
So what's your stroke?

157
00:10:02.871 --> 00:10:04.623
Sorry, my what?

158
00:10:04.665 --> 00:10:07.793
Waiter/actor,
waiter/model, waiter/writer?

159
00:10:07.835 --> 00:10:10.504
Well, I'm a comedian.

160
00:10:10.545 --> 00:10:13.841
We could use a comedian. We
all like to laugh. I know I used to.

161
00:10:13.882 --> 00:10:15.509
Well, I'm just
starting out really.

162
00:10:15.550 --> 00:10:18.178
Working on my
"unique comedy stylings."

163
00:10:18.219 --> 00:10:21.222
Not jokes so much, more
sort of wry, little observations.

164
00:10:21.974 --> 00:10:23.934
<i><font face="monospaceSansSerif" color="white">Ay caramba!</i>

165
00:10:23.976 --> 00:10:25.435
I've got this whole bit
at the moment

166
00:10:25.477 --> 00:10:27.980
about the difference
between men and women.

167
00:10:28.022 --> 00:10:30.774
How blokes, when they see
a girl they fancy, they get all...

168
00:10:30.816 --> 00:10:33.151
Toilets. Staff toilets. Oh.

169
00:10:33.193 --> 00:10:35.029
Sorry. You were saying?

170
00:10:35.070 --> 00:10:37.948
No, no. I'm doing an open mic
tonight if you were interested.

171
00:10:37.990 --> 00:10:41.576
At The House of Laffs,
spelled L-A-F-F-S.

172
00:10:41.618 --> 00:10:43.161
It's not a date or anything.

173
00:10:43.203 --> 00:10:44.412
You've probably got a
boyfriend anyway, have you?

174
00:10:46.707 --> 00:10:49.835
Ian, I'd love to come,
but after work,

175
00:10:49.877 --> 00:10:51.920
I like to head home,
comfort eat, weep.

176
00:10:54.130 --> 00:10:56.884
So what about you, Emma?
What's your stroke?

177
00:10:56.925 --> 00:10:58.969
What do you really do?

178
00:10:59.011 --> 00:11:01.596
Uh, this. This is what I do.

179
00:11:02.806 --> 00:11:04.808
Still, it's not forever, is it?

180
00:11:10.064 --> 00:11:13.859
My room still smells. Tilly's
sending me mad. The flat's a dump.

181
00:11:13.901 --> 00:11:16.028
I keep finding
teeth marks in the cheese

182
00:11:16.070 --> 00:11:18.238
<i><font face="monospaceSansSerif" color="white">and her big gray bras
<font face="monospaceSansSerif" color="white">soaking in the sink.</i>

183
00:11:18.279 --> 00:11:19.280
Look, I'm sure it's
not a complete disaster.

184
00:11:20.615 --> 00:11:22.826
London's swallowed me up.

185
00:11:25.871 --> 00:11:28.040
I thought I'd make a difference,
but no one knows I'm here.

186
00:11:28.082 --> 00:11:30.125
Listen, listen. Nothing
truly good was ever easy.

187
00:11:30.166 --> 00:11:30.876
<i><font face="monospaceSansSerif" color="white">Who said that?</i>

188
00:11:31.710 --> 00:11:32.920
<i><font face="monospaceSansSerif" color="white">You did.</i>

189
00:11:32.961 --> 00:11:36.006
Did I? That's annoying.

190
00:11:36.048 --> 00:11:39.384
I'm sorry for moaning. I
just... I really wanted to hear...

191
00:11:39.426 --> 00:11:40.719
How's teaching? How's Paris?

192
00:11:41.553 --> 00:11:43.221
It's good, Em.

193
00:11:43.263 --> 00:11:45.807
You know,
truly, really fulfilling.

194
00:11:45.849 --> 00:11:47.935
<i><font face="monospaceSansSerif" color="white">Well, don't sleep with
<font face="monospaceSansSerif" color="white">any of your students.</i>

195
00:11:47.976 --> 00:11:50.020
<i><font face="monospaceSansSerif" color="white">It's unethical <font face="monospaceSansSerif" color="white">and predictable.</i>

196
00:11:50.062 --> 00:11:51.271
It's good advice, Em. Thank you.

197
00:11:52.480 --> 00:11:54.108
<i><font face="monospaceSansSerif" color="white">But I've got to go
<font face="monospaceSansSerif" color="white">and have lunch with Mum.</i>

198
00:11:54.149 --> 00:11:57.527
<i><font face="monospaceSansSerif" color="white">Well, <font face="monospaceSansSerif" color="white">apologize again, will you?</i>

199
00:11:57.569 --> 00:11:59.738
I didn't mean to
call your dad a fascist.

200
00:11:59.780 --> 00:12:01.656
A bourgeois fascist.

201
00:12:01.698 --> 00:12:04.409
Say sorry and, Dexter...

202
00:12:04.451 --> 00:12:05.827
My money's running out. Em?

203
00:12:05.869 --> 00:12:07.829
Can you hear me? Dex? Dex?

204
00:12:14.795 --> 00:12:16.171
I miss you.

205
00:12:40.946 --> 00:12:42.114
Forty-five minutes late.

206
00:12:42.156 --> 00:12:43.573
Yeah, well, I got waylaid.

207
00:12:43.615 --> 00:12:45.117
And where were you last night?

208
00:12:45.159 --> 00:12:46.868
Language school disco.

209
00:12:46.910 --> 00:12:48.703
Was it fun? No, it was hell.

210
00:12:50.413 --> 00:12:53.083
Tell me, who's been writing
you all those long letters?

211
00:12:53.125 --> 00:12:55.210
That is none of your business.

212
00:12:55.251 --> 00:12:58.172
Was it that girl
who came to stay?

213
00:12:58.213 --> 00:12:58.922
Yeah. Well, Emma and I
are just good friends.

214
00:13:02.801 --> 00:13:05.720
How much holiday do you need?

215
00:13:05.762 --> 00:13:08.140
I'm not on holiday.
I'm teaching English.

216
00:13:08.182 --> 00:13:08.932
Dexter.

217
00:13:12.019 --> 00:13:14.021
Isn't that Alain Delon?

218
00:13:14.062 --> 00:13:16.106
What? Oh, no. It's your father.

219
00:13:18.859 --> 00:13:21.028
Picking his corns. Stop it.

220
00:13:23.864 --> 00:13:26.200
Take me for lunch tomorrow,
will you?

221
00:13:26.241 --> 00:13:29.369
Just you and me. Somewhere
quiet with white tablecloths.

222
00:13:29.410 --> 00:13:31.579
I want to talk to you.

223
00:13:31.621 --> 00:13:32.622
Why? Is something wrong?

224
00:13:32.664 --> 00:13:35.209
No. Nothing's wrong.

225
00:13:35.250 --> 00:13:36.417
Then why do we need to talk?

226
00:13:36.459 --> 00:13:37.794
Do I need a reason?

227
00:13:38.837 --> 00:13:40.672
There you are. Degenerate.

228
00:13:46.469 --> 00:13:48.972
Now, I thought
you might want these.

229
00:13:50.265 --> 00:13:54.019
Oh, thank you, my love.

230
00:13:54.061 --> 00:13:57.772
So what's for supper?
Please, God, not French food.

231
00:14:13.247 --> 00:14:15.415
Golden Boy wants
to see you. Hmm?

232
00:14:15.456 --> 00:14:17.125
He's got a new one.

233
00:14:23.506 --> 00:14:25.383
Good night. Good night.

234
00:14:25.425 --> 00:14:26.134
Night. Good night.

235
00:14:27.510 --> 00:14:28.595
Have a good one.

236
00:14:28.636 --> 00:14:30.305
We were just kissing.

237
00:14:30.346 --> 00:14:33.850
You were trying to fit her
entire head in your mouth.

238
00:14:33.892 --> 00:14:36.770
People have enough trouble
keeping the food down as it is.

239
00:14:36.811 --> 00:14:38.563
And what does she
see in you, anyway?

240
00:14:38.605 --> 00:14:40.481
Well, she says I'm complicated.

241
00:14:42.109 --> 00:14:43.110
You're just spoiled.

242
00:14:47.239 --> 00:14:50.242
I got offered
the job of manager today.

243
00:14:50.284 --> 00:14:53.203
They told me they wanted
someone who wasn't going anywhere.

244
00:14:53.245 --> 00:14:55.663
All right, Em, listen. I think you
should take a bottle of tequila,

245
00:14:55.705 --> 00:14:57.332
I think you should
walk out the door,

246
00:14:57.373 --> 00:14:58.583
and I don't think you
need to ever come back.

247
00:14:58.625 --> 00:15:00.710
But my job is my life.

248
00:15:00.752 --> 00:15:03.504
You can't throw away years
of your life just because,

249
00:15:03.546 --> 00:15:05.799
well, you think it's funny.

250
00:15:05.840 --> 00:15:08.343
My hair smells of cheese.
Monterey Jack.

251
00:15:09.844 --> 00:15:12.264
Look, I thought you
